39def comp(z1, z2, tol=None): 

40 """Return a bool indicating whether the error between z1 and z2 is <= tol. 

41 

42 If ``tol`` is None then True will be returned if there is a significant 

43 difference between the numbers: ``abs(z1 - z2)*10**p <= 1/2`` where ``p`` 

44 is the lower of the precisions of the values. A comparison of strings will 

45 be made if ``z1`` is a Number and a) ``z2`` is a string or b) ``tol`` is '' 

46 and ``z2`` is a Number. 

47 

48 When ``tol`` is a nonzero value, if z2 is non-zero and ``|z1| > 1`` 

49 the error is normalized by ``|z1|``, so if you want to see if the 

50 absolute error between ``z1`` and ``z2`` is <= ``tol`` then call this 

51 as ``comp(z1 - z2, 0, tol)``. 

52 """ 

53 if type(z2) is str: 

54 if not isinstance(z1, Number): 

55 raise ValueError('when z2 is a str z1 must be a Number') 

56 return str(z1) == z2 

57 if not z1: 

58 z1, z2 = z2, z1 

59 if not z1: 

60 return True 

61 if not tol: 

62 if tol is None: 

63 if type(z2) is str and getattr(z1, 'is_Number', False): 

64 return str(z1) == z2 

65 a, b = Float(z1), Float(z2) 

66 return int(abs(a - b)*10**prec_to_dps( 

67 min(a._prec, b._prec)))*2 <= 1 

68 elif all(getattr(i, 'is_Number', False) for i in (z1, z2)): 

69 return z1._prec == z2._prec and str(z1) == str(z2) 

70 raise ValueError('exact comparison requires two Numbers') 

71 diff = abs(z1 - z2) 

72 az1 = abs(z1) 

73 if z2 and az1 > 1: 

74 return diff/az1 <= tol 

75 else: 

76 return diff <= tol

79def mpf_norm(mpf, prec): 

80 """Return the mpf tuple normalized appropriately for the indicated 

81 precision after doing a check to see if zero should be returned or 

82 not when the mantissa is 0. ``mpf_normlize`` always assumes that this 

83 is zero, but it may not be since the mantissa for mpf's values "+inf", 

84 "-inf" and "nan" have a mantissa of zero, too. 

85 

86 Note: this is not intended to validate a given mpf tuple, so sending 

87 mpf tuples that were not created by mpmath may produce bad results. This 

88 is only a wrapper to ``mpf_normalize`` which provides the check for non- 

89 zero mpfs that have a 0 for the mantissa. 

90 """ 

91 sign, man, expt, bc = mpf 

92 if not man: 

93 # hack for mpf_normalize which does not do this; 

94 # it assumes that if man is zero the result is 0 

95 # (see issue 6639)

105 rv = mpf_normalize(sign, MPZ(man), expt, bc, prec, rnd) 

106 return rv

135def _decimal_to_Rational_prec(dec): 

136 """Convert an ordinary decimal instance to a Rational.""" 

137 if not dec.is_finite(): 

138 raise TypeError("dec must be finite, got %s." % dec) 

139 s, d, e = dec.as_tuple() 

140 prec = len(d) 

141 if e >= 0: # it's an integer 

142 rv = Integer(int(dec)) 

143 else: 

144 s = (-1)**s 

145 d = sum([di*10**i for i, di in enumerate(reversed(d))]) 

146 rv = Rational(s*d, 10**-e) 

147 return rv, prec

160def igcd(*args): 

161 """Computes nonnegative integer greatest common divisor. 

162 

163 The algorithm is based on the well known Euclid's algorithm. To 

164 improve speed, igcd() has its own caching mechanism implemented. 

165 

166 Examples 

167 ======== 

168 

169 >>> from sympy.core.numbers import igcd 

170 >>> igcd(2, 4) 

171 2 

172 >>> igcd(5, 10, 15) 

173 5 

174 

175 """ 

176 if len(args) < 2: 

177 raise TypeError( 

178 'igcd() takes at least 2 arguments (%s given)' % len(args)) 

179 args_temp = [abs(as_int(i)) for i in args] 

180 if 1 in args_temp: 

181 return 1 

182 a = args_temp.pop() 

183 for b in args_temp: 

184 a = igcd2(a, b) if b else a 

185 return a

192 """Compute gcd of two Python integers a and b.""" 

193 if (a.bit_length() > BIGBITS and 

194 b.bit_length() > BIGBITS): 

195 return igcd_lehmer(a, b) 

196 

197 a, b = abs(a), abs(b) 

198 while b: 

199 a, b = b, a % b 

200 return a

203# Use Lehmer's algorithm only for very large numbers. 

204# The limit could be different on Python 2.7 and 3.x.

206BIGBITS = 5000 

207def igcd_lehmer(a, b): 

208 """Computes greatest common divisor of two integers. 

209 

210 Euclid's algorithm for the computation of the greatest 

211 common divisor gcd(a, b) of two (positive) integers 

212 a and b is based on the division identity 

213 a = q*b + r, 

214 where the quotient q and the remainder r are integers 

215 and 0 <= r < b. Then each common divisor of a and b 

216 divides r, and it follows that gcd(a, b) == gcd(b, r). 

217 The algorithm works by constructing the sequence 

218 r0, r1, r2, ..., where r0 = a, r1 = b, and each rn 

219 is the remainder from the division of the two preceding 

220 elements. 

221 

222 In Python, q = a // b and r = a % b are obtained by the 

223 floor division and the remainder operations, respectively. 

224 These are the most expensive arithmetic operations, especially 

225 for large a and b. 

226 

227 Lehmer's algorithm is based on the observation that the quotients 

228 qn = r(n-1) // rn are in general small integers even 

229 when a and b are very large. Hence the quotients can be 

230 usually determined from a relatively small number of most 

231 significant bits. 

232 

233 The efficiency of the algorithm is further enhanced by not 

234 computing each long remainder in Euclid's sequence. The remainders 

235 are linear combinations of a and b with integer coefficients 

236 derived from the quotients. The coefficients can be computed 

237 as far as the quotients can be determined from the chosen 

238 most significant parts of a and b. Only then a new pair of 

239 consecutive remainders is computed and the algorithm starts 

240 anew with this pair. 

241 

242 References 

243 ========== 

244 

245 .. [1] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lehmer%27s_GCD_algorithm 

246 

247 """ 

248 a, b = abs(as_int(a)), abs(as_int(b)) 

249 if a < b: 

250 a, b = b, a 

251 

252 # The algorithm works by using one or two digit division 

253 # whenever possible. The outer loop will replace the 

254 # pair (a, b) with a pair of shorter consecutive elements 

255 # of the Euclidean gcd sequence until a and b 

256 # fit into two Python (long) int digits. 

257 nbits = 2*int_info.bits_per_digit 

258 

259 while a.bit_length() > nbits and b != 0: 

260 # Quotients are mostly small integers that can 

261 # be determined from most significant bits. 

262 n = a.bit_length() - nbits 

263 x, y = int(a >> n), int(b >> n) # most significant bits 

264 

265 # Elements of the Euclidean gcd sequence are linear 

266 # combinations of a and b with integer coefficients. 

267 # Compute the coefficients of consecutive pairs 

268 # a' = A*a + B*b, b' = C*a + D*b 

269 # using small integer arithmetic as far as possible. 

270 A, B, C, D = 1, 0, 0, 1 # initial values 

271 

272 while True: 

273 # The coefficients alternate in sign while looping. 

274 # The inner loop combines two steps to keep track 

275 # of the signs. 

276 

277 # At this point we have 

278 # A > 0, B <= 0, C <= 0, D > 0, 

279 # x' = x + B <= x < x" = x + A, 

280 # y' = y + C <= y < y" = y + D, 

281 # and 

282 # x'*N <= a' < x"*N, y'*N <= b' < y"*N, 

283 # where N = 2**n. 

284 

285 # Now, if y' > 0, and x"//y' and x'//y" agree, 

286 # then their common value is equal to q = a'//b'. 

287 # In addition, 

288 # x'%y" = x' - q*y" < x" - q*y' = x"%y', 

289 # and 

290 # (x'%y")*N < a'%b' < (x"%y')*N. 

291 

292 # On the other hand, we also have x//y == q, 

293 # and therefore 

294 # x'%y" = x + B - q*(y + D) = x%y + B', 

295 # x"%y' = x + A - q*(y + C) = x%y + A', 

296 # where 

297 # B' = B - q*D < 0, A' = A - q*C > 0. 

298 

299 if y + C <= 0: 

300 break 

301 q = (x + A) // (y + C) 

302 

303 # Now x'//y" <= q, and equality holds if 

304 # x' - q*y" = (x - q*y) + (B - q*D) >= 0. 

305 # This is a minor optimization to avoid division. 

306 x_qy, B_qD = x - q*y, B - q*D 

307 if x_qy + B_qD < 0: 

308 break 

309 

310 # Next step in the Euclidean sequence. 

311 x, y = y, x_qy 

312 A, B, C, D = C, D, A - q*C, B_qD 

313 

314 # At this point the signs of the coefficients 

315 # change and their roles are interchanged. 

316 # A <= 0, B > 0, C > 0, D < 0, 

317 # x' = x + A <= x < x" = x + B, 

318 # y' = y + D < y < y" = y + C. 

319 

320 if y + D <= 0: 

321 break 

322 q = (x + B) // (y + D) 

323 x_qy, A_qC = x - q*y, A - q*C 

324 if x_qy + A_qC < 0: 

325 break 

326 

327 x, y = y, x_qy 

328 A, B, C, D = C, D, A_qC, B - q*D 

329 # Now the conditions on top of the loop 

330 # are again satisfied. 

331 # A > 0, B < 0, C < 0, D > 0. 

332 

333 if B == 0: 

334 # This can only happen when y == 0 in the beginning 

335 # and the inner loop does nothing. 

336 # Long division is forced. 

337 a, b = b, a % b 

338 continue 

339 

340 # Compute new long arguments using the coefficients. 

341 a, b = A*a + B*b, C*a + D*b 

342 

343 # Small divisors. Finish with the standard algorithm. 

344 while b: 

345 a, b = b, a % b 

346 

347 return a

350def ilcm(*args): 

351 """Computes integer least common multiple. 

352 

353 Examples 

354 ======== 

355 

356 >>> from sympy.core.numbers import ilcm 

357 >>> ilcm(5, 10) 

358 10 

359 >>> ilcm(7, 3) 

360 21 

361 >>> ilcm(5, 10, 15) 

362 30 

363 

364 """ 

365 if len(args) < 2: 

366 raise TypeError( 

367 'ilcm() takes at least 2 arguments (%s given)' % len(args)) 

368 if 0 in args: 

369 return 0 

370 a = args[0] 

371 for b in args[1:]: 

372 a = a // igcd(a, b) * b # since gcd(a,b) | a 

373 return a

376def igcdex(a, b): 

377 """Returns x, y, g such that g = x*a + y*b = gcd(a, b). 

378 

379 >>> from sympy.core.numbers import igcdex 

380 >>> igcdex(2, 3) 

381 (-1, 1, 1) 

382 >>> igcdex(10, 12) 

383 (-1, 1, 2) 

384 

385 >>> x, y, g = igcdex(100, 2004) 

386 >>> x, y, g 

387 (-20, 1, 4) 

388 >>> x*100 + y*2004 

389 4 

390 

391 """ 

392 if (not a) and (not b): 

393 return (0, 1, 0) 

394 

395 if not a: 

396 return (0, b//abs(b), abs(b)) 

397 if not b: 

398 return (a//abs(a), 0, abs(a)) 

399 

400 if a < 0: 

401 a, x_sign = -a, -1 

402 else: 

403 x_sign = 1 

404 

405 if b < 0: 

406 b, y_sign = -b, -1 

407 else: 

408 y_sign = 1 

409 

410 x, y, r, s = 1, 0, 0, 1 

411 

412 while b: 

413 (c, q) = (a % b, a // b) 

414 (a, b, r, s, x, y) = (b, c, x - q*r, y - q*s, r, s) 

415 

416 return (x*x_sign, y*y_sign, a)

419def mod_inverse(a, m): 

420 """ 

421 Return the number c such that, (a * c) = 1 (mod m) 

422 where c has the same sign as m. If no such value exists, 

423 a ValueError is raised. 

424 

425 Examples 

426 ======== 

427 

428 >>> from sympy import S 

429 >>> from sympy.core.numbers import mod_inverse 

430 

431 Suppose we wish to find multiplicative inverse x of 

432 3 modulo 11. This is the same as finding x such 

433 that 3 * x = 1 (mod 11). One value of x that satisfies 

434 this congruence is 4. Because 3 * 4 = 12 and 12 = 1 (mod 11). 

435 This is the value return by mod_inverse: 

436 

437 >>> mod_inverse(3, 11) 

438 4 

439 >>> mod_inverse(-3, 11) 

440 7 

441 

442 When there is a common factor between the numerators of 

443 ``a`` and ``m`` the inverse does not exist: 

444 

445 >>> mod_inverse(2, 4) 

446 Traceback (most recent call last): 

447 ... 

448 ValueError: inverse of 2 mod 4 does not exist 

449 

450 >>> mod_inverse(S(2)/7, S(5)/2) 

451 7/2 

452 

453 References 

454 ========== 

455 - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse 

456 - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm 

457 """ 

458 c = None 

459 try: 

460 a, m = as_int(a), as_int(m) 

461 if m != 1 and m != -1: 

462 x, y, g = igcdex(a, m) 

463 if g == 1: 

464 c = x % m 

465 except ValueError: 

466 a, m = sympify(a), sympify(m) 

467 if not (a.is_number and m.is_number): 

468 raise TypeError(filldedent(''' 

469 Expected numbers for arguments; symbolic `mod_inverse` 

470 is not implemented 

471 but symbolic expressions can be handled with the 

472 similar function, 

473 sympy.polys.polytools.invert''')) 

474 big = (m > 1) 

475 if not (big is S.true or big is S.false): 

476 raise ValueError('m > 1 did not evaluate; try to simplify %s' % m) 

477 elif big: 

478 c = 1/a 

479 if c is None: 

480 raise ValueError('inverse of %s (mod %s) does not exist' % (a, m)) 

481 return c

484class Number(AtomicExpr): 

485 """Represents atomic numbers in SymPy. 

486 

487 Floating point numbers are represented by the Float class. 

488 Rational numbers (of any size) are represented by the Rational class. 

489 Integer numbers (of any size) are represented by the Integer class. 

490 Float and Rational are subclasses of Number; Integer is a subclass 

491 of Rational. 

492 

493 For example, ``2/3`` is represented as ``Rational(2, 3)`` which is 

494 a different object from the floating point number obtained with 

495 Python division ``2/3``. Even for numbers that are exactly 

496 represented in binary, there is a difference between how two forms, 

497 such as ``Rational(1, 2)`` and ``Float(0.5)``, are used in SymPy. 

498 The rational form is to be preferred in symbolic computations. 

499 

500 Other kinds of numbers, such as algebraic numbers ``sqrt(2)`` or 

501 complex numbers ``3 + 4*I``, are not instances of Number class as 

502 they are not atomic. 

503 

504 See Also 

505 ======== 

506 

507 Float, Integer, Rational 

508 """ 

509 is_commutative = True 

510 is_number = True 

511 is_Number = True 

512 

513 __slots__ = []

657 return S.NaN 

658 elif self.is_positive: 

659 return S.NegativeInfinity 

660 else: 

661 return S.Infinity 

662 elif isinstance(other, Tuple): 

663 return NotImplemented 

664 return AtomicExpr.__mul__(self, other)

669 if other is S.NaN:

763class Float(Number): 

764 """Represent a floating-point number of arbitrary precision. 

765 

766 Examples 

767 ======== 

768 

769 >>> from sympy import Float 

770 >>> Float(3.5) 

771 3.50000000000000 

772 >>> Float(3) 

773 3.00000000000000 

774 

775 Creating Floats from strings (and Python ``int`` and ``long`` 

776 types) will give a minimum precision of 15 digits, but the 

777 precision will automatically increase to capture all digits 

778 entered. 

779 

780 >>> Float(1) 

781 1.00000000000000 

782 >>> Float(10**20) 

783 100000000000000000000. 

784 >>> Float('1e20') 

785 100000000000000000000. 

786 

787 However, *floating-point* numbers (Python ``float`` types) retain 

788 only 15 digits of precision: 

789 

790 >>> Float(1e20) 

791 1.00000000000000e+20 

792 >>> Float(1.23456789123456789) 

793 1.23456789123457 

794 

795 It may be preferable to enter high-precision decimal numbers 

796 as strings: 

797 

798 Float('1.23456789123456789') 

799 1.23456789123456789 

800 

801 The desired number of digits can also be specified: 

802 

803 >>> Float('1e-3', 3) 

804 0.00100 

805 >>> Float(100, 4) 

806 100.0 

807 

808 Float can automatically count significant figures if a null string 

809 is sent for the precision; space are also allowed in the string. (Auto- 

810 counting is only allowed for strings, ints and longs). 

811 

812 >>> Float('123 456 789 . 123 456', '') 

813 123456789.123456 

814 >>> Float('12e-3', '') 

815 0.012 

816 >>> Float(3, '') 

817 3. 

818 

819 If a number is written in scientific notation, only the digits before the 

820 exponent are considered significant if a decimal appears, otherwise the 

821 "e" signifies only how to move the decimal: 

822 

823 >>> Float('60.e2', '') # 2 digits significant 

824 6.0e+3 

825 >>> Float('60e2', '') # 4 digits significant 

826 6000. 

827 >>> Float('600e-2', '') # 3 digits significant 

828 6.00 

829 

830 Notes 

831 ===== 

832 

833 Floats are inexact by their nature unless their value is a binary-exact 

834 value. 

835 

836 >>> approx, exact = Float(.1, 1), Float(.125, 1) 

837 

838 For calculation purposes, evalf needs to be able to change the precision 

839 but this will not increase the accuracy of the inexact value. The 

840 following is the most accurate 5-digit approximation of a value of 0.1 

841 that had only 1 digit of precision: 

842 

843 >>> approx.evalf(5) 

844 0.099609 

845 

846 By contrast, 0.125 is exact in binary (as it is in base 10) and so it 

847 can be passed to Float or evalf to obtain an arbitrary precision with 

848 matching accuracy: 

849 

850 >>> Float(exact, 5) 

851 0.12500 

852 >>> exact.evalf(20) 

853 0.12500000000000000000 

854 

855 Trying to make a high-precision Float from a float is not disallowed, 

856 but one must keep in mind that the *underlying float* (not the apparent 

857 decimal value) is being obtained with high precision. For example, 0.3 

858 does not have a finite binary representation. The closest rational is 

859 the fraction 5404319552844595/2**54. So if you try to obtain a Float of 

860 0.3 to 20 digits of precision you will not see the same thing as 0.3 

861 followed by 19 zeros: 

862 

863 >>> Float(0.3, 20) 

864 0.29999999999999998890 

865 

866 If you want a 20-digit value of the decimal 0.3 (not the floating point 

867 approximation of 0.3) you should send the 0.3 as a string. The underlying 

868 representation is still binary but a higher precision than Python's float 

869 is used: 

870 

871 >>> Float('0.3', 20) 

872 0.30000000000000000000 

873 

874 Although you can increase the precision of an existing Float using Float 

875 it will not increase the accuracy -- the underlying value is not changed: 

876 

877 >>> def show(f): # binary rep of Float 

878 ... from sympy import Mul, Pow 

879 ... s, m, e, b = f._mpf_ 

880 ... v = Mul(int(m), Pow(2, int(e), evaluate=False), evaluate=False) 

881 ... print('%s at prec=%s' % (v, f._prec)) 

882 ... 

883 >>> t = Float('0.3', 3) 

884 >>> show(t) 

885 4915/2**14 at prec=13 

886 >>> show(Float(t, 20)) # higher prec, not higher accuracy 

887 4915/2**14 at prec=70 

888 >>> show(Float(t, 2)) # lower prec 

889 307/2**10 at prec=10 

890 

891 The same thing happens when evalf is used on a Float: 

892 

893 >>> show(t.evalf(20)) 

894 4915/2**14 at prec=70 

895 >>> show(t.evalf(2)) 

896 307/2**10 at prec=10 

897 

898 Finally, Floats can be instantiated with an mpf tuple (n, c, p) to 

899 produce the number (-1)**n*c*2**p: 

900 

901 >>> n, c, p = 1, 5, 0 

902 >>> (-1)**n*c*2**p 

903 -5 

904 >>> Float((1, 5, 0)) 

905 -5.00000000000000 

906 

907 An actual mpf tuple also contains the number of bits in c as the last 

908 element of the tuple: 

909 

910 >>> _._mpf_ 

911 (1, 5, 0, 3) 

912 

913 This is not needed for instantiation and is not the same thing as the 

914 precision. The mpf tuple and the precision are two separate quantities 

915 that Float tracks. 

916 

917 """ 

918 __slots__ = ['_mpf_', '_prec'] 

919 

920 # A Float represents many real numbers, 

921 # both rational and irrational. 

922 is_rational = None 

923 is_irrational = None 

924 is_number = True 

925 

926 is_real = True 

927 

928 is_Float = True

930 def __new__(cls, num, dps=None, prec=None, precision=None): 

931 if prec is not None: 

932 SymPyDeprecationWarning( 

933 feature="Using 'prec=XX' to denote decimal precision", 

934 useinstead="'dps=XX' for decimal precision and 'precision=XX' "\ 

935 "for binary precision", 

936 issue=12820, 

937 deprecated_since_version="1.1").warn() 

938 dps = prec 

939 del prec # avoid using this deprecated kwarg 

940 

941 if dps is not None and precision is not None: 

942 raise ValueError('Both decimal and binary precision supplied. ' 

943 'Supply only one. ') 

944 

945 if isinstance(num, string_types): 

946 num = num.replace(' ', '') 

947 if num.startswith('.') and len(num) > 1: 

948 num = '0' + num 

949 elif num.startswith('-.') and len(num) > 2: 

950 num = '-0.' + num[2:] 

951 elif isinstance(num, float) and num == 0: 

952 num = '0' 

953 elif isinstance(num, (SYMPY_INTS, Integer)): 

954 num = str(num) # faster than mlib.from_int 

955 elif num is S.Infinity: 

956 num = '+inf' 

957 elif num is S.NegativeInfinity: 

958 num = '-inf' 

959 elif type(num).__module__ == 'numpy': # support for numpy datatypes 

960 num = _convert_numpy_types(num) 

961 elif isinstance(num, mpmath.mpf): 

962 if precision is None: 

963 if dps is None: 

964 precision = num.context.prec 

965 num = num._mpf_ 

966 

967 if dps is None and precision is None: 

968 dps = 15 

969 if isinstance(num, Float): 

970 return num 

971 if isinstance(num, string_types) and _literal_float(num): 

972 try: 

973 Num = decimal.Decimal(num) 

974 except decimal.InvalidOperation: 

975 pass 

976 else: 

977 isint = '.' not in num 

978 num, dps = _decimal_to_Rational_prec(Num) 

979 if num.is_Integer and isint: 

980 dps = max(dps, len(str(num).lstrip('-'))) 

981 dps = max(15, dps) 

982 precision = mlib.libmpf.dps_to_prec(dps) 

983 elif precision == '' and dps is None or precision is None and dps == '': 

984 if not isinstance(num, string_types): 

985 raise ValueError('The null string can only be used when ' 

986 'the number to Float is passed as a string or an integer.') 

987 ok = None 

988 if _literal_float(num): 

989 try: 

990 Num = decimal.Decimal(num) 

991 except decimal.InvalidOperation: 

992 pass 

993 else: 

994 isint = '.' not in num 

995 num, dps = _decimal_to_Rational_prec(Num) 

996 if num.is_Integer and isint: 

997 dps = max(dps, len(str(num).lstrip('-'))) 

998 precision = mlib.libmpf.dps_to_prec(dps) 

999 ok = True 

1000 if ok is None: 

1001 raise ValueError('string-float not recognized: %s' % num) 

1002 

1003 # decimal precision(dps) is set and maybe binary precision(precision) 

1004 # as well.From here on binary precision is used to compute the Float. 

1005 # Hence, if supplied use binary precision else translate from decimal 

1006 # precision. 

1007 

1008 if precision is None or precision == '': 

1009 precision = mlib.libmpf.dps_to_prec(dps) 

1010 

1011 precision = int(precision) 

1012 

1013 if isinstance(num, float): 

1014 _mpf_ = mlib.from_float(num, precision, rnd) 

1015 elif isinstance(num, string_types): 

1016 _mpf_ = mlib.from_str(num, precision, rnd) 

1017 elif isinstance(num, decimal.Decimal): 

1018 if num.is_finite(): 

1019 _mpf_ = mlib.from_str(str(num), precision, rnd) 

1020 elif num.is_nan(): 

1021 _mpf_ = _mpf_nan 

1022 elif num.is_infinite(): 

1023 if num > 0: 

1024 _mpf_ = _mpf_inf 

1025 else: 

1026 _mpf_ = _mpf_ninf 

1027 else: 

1028 raise ValueError("unexpected decimal value %s" % str(num)) 

1029 elif isinstance(num, tuple) and len(num) in (3, 4): 

1030 if type(num[1]) is str: 

1031 # it's a hexadecimal (coming from a pickled object) 

1032 # assume that it is in standard form 

1033 num = list(num) 

1034 # If we're loading an object pickled in Python 2 into 

1035 # Python 3, we may need to strip a tailing 'L' because 

1036 # of a shim for int on Python 3, see issue #13470. 

1037 if num[1].endswith('L'): 

1038 num[1] = num[1][:-1] 

1039 num[1] = MPZ(num[1], 16) 

1040 _mpf_ = tuple(num) 

1041 else: 

1042 if len(num) == 4: 

1043 # handle normalization hack 

1044 return Float._new(num, precision) 

1045 else: 

1046 return (S.NegativeOne**num[0]*num[1]*S(2)**num[2]).evalf(precision) 

1047 else: 

1048 try: 

1049 _mpf_ = num._as_mpf_val(precision) 

1050 except (NotImplementedError, AttributeError): 

1051 _mpf_ = mpmath.mpf(num, prec=precision)._mpf_ 

1052 

1053 # special cases 

1054 if _mpf_ == _mpf_zero: 

1055 pass # we want a Float 

1056 elif _mpf_ == _mpf_nan: 

1057 return S.NaN 

1058 

1059 obj = Expr.__new__(cls) 

1060 obj._mpf_ = _mpf_ 

1061 obj._prec = precision 

1062 return obj

1069 elif _mpf_ == _mpf_nan: 

1070 return S.NaN

1072 obj = Expr.__new__(cls) 

1073 obj._mpf_ = mpf_norm(_mpf_, _prec)

1075 obj._prec = _prec

1201 def _eval_power(self, expt): 

1202 """ 

1203 expt is symbolic object but not equal to 0, 1 

1204 

1205 (-p)**r -> exp(r*log(-p)) -> exp(r*(log(p) + I*Pi)) -> 

1206 -> p**r*(sin(Pi*r) + cos(Pi*r)*I) 

1207 """ 

1208 if self == 0: 

1209 if expt.is_positive: 

1210 return S.Zero 

1211 if expt.is_negative: 

1212 return Float('inf') 

1213 if isinstance(expt, Number): 

1214 if isinstance(expt, Integer): 

1215 prec = self._prec 

1216 return Float._new( 

1217 mlib.mpf_pow_int(self._mpf_, expt.p, prec, rnd), prec) 

1218 elif isinstance(expt, Rational) and \ 

1219 expt.p == 1 and expt.q % 2 and self.is_negative: 

1220 return Pow(S.NegativeOne, expt, evaluate=False)*( 

1221 -self)._eval_power(expt) 

1222 expt, prec = expt._as_mpf_op(self._prec) 

1223 mpfself = self._mpf_ 

1224 try: 

1225 y = mpf_pow(mpfself, expt, prec, rnd) 

1226 return Float._new(y, prec) 

1227 except mlib.ComplexResult: 

1228 re, im = mlib.mpc_pow( 

1229 (mpfself, _mpf_zero), (expt, _mpf_zero), prec, rnd) 

1230 return Float._new(re, prec) + \ 

1231 Float._new(im, prec)*S.ImaginaryUnit 

1232 

1233 def __abs__(self): 

1234 return Float._new(mlib.mpf_abs(self._mpf_), self._prec)

1237 if self._mpf_ == _mpf_zero: 

1238 return 0 

1239 return int(mlib.to_int(self._mpf_)) # uses round_fast = round_down

1243 def __eq__(self, other): 

1244 if isinstance(other, float): 

1245 # coerce to Float at same precision 

1246 o = Float(other) 

1247 try: 

1248 ompf = o._as_mpf_val(self._prec) 

1249 except ValueError: 

1250 return False 

1251 return bool(mlib.mpf_eq(self._mpf_, ompf)) 

1252 try: 

1253 other = _sympify(other) 

1254 except SympifyError: 

1255 return NotImplemented 

1256 if other.is_NumberSymbol: 

1257 if other.is_irrational: 

1258 return False 

1259 return other.__eq__(self) 

1260 if other.is_Float: 

1261 return bool(mlib.mpf_eq(self._mpf_, other._mpf_)) 

1262 if other.is_Number: 

1263 # numbers should compare at the same precision; 

1264 # all _as_mpf_val routines should be sure to abide 

1265 # by the request to change the prec if necessary; if 

1266 # they don't, the equality test will fail since it compares 

1267 # the mpf tuples 

1268 ompf = other._as_mpf_val(self._prec) 

1269 return bool(mlib.mpf_eq(self._mpf_, ompf)) 

1270 return False # Float != non-Number

1273 return not self == other

1275 def __gt__(self, other): 

1276 try: 

1277 other = _sympify(other) 

1278 except SympifyError: 

1279 raise TypeError("Invalid comparison %s > %s" % (self, other)) 

1280 if other.is_NumberSymbol: 

1281 return other.__lt__(self) 

1282 if other.is_Rational and not other.is_Integer: 

1283 self *= other.q 

1284 other = _sympify(other.p)

1364class Rational(Number): 

1365 """Represents rational numbers (p/q) of any size. 

1366 

1367 Examples 

1368 ======== 

1369 

1370 >>> from sympy import Rational, nsimplify, S, pi 

1371 >>> Rational(1, 2) 

1372 1/2 

1373 

1374 Rational is unprejudiced in accepting input. If a float is passed, the 

1375 underlying value of the binary representation will be returned: 

1376 

1377 >>> Rational(.5) 

1378 1/2 

1379 >>> Rational(.2) 

1380 3602879701896397/18014398509481984 

1381 

1382 If the simpler representation of the float is desired then consider 

1383 limiting the denominator to the desired value or convert the float to 

1384 a string (which is roughly equivalent to limiting the denominator to 

1385 10**12): 

1386 

1387 >>> Rational(str(.2)) 

1388 1/5 

1389 >>> Rational(.2).limit_denominator(10**12) 

1390 1/5 

1391 

1392 An arbitrarily precise Rational is obtained when a string literal is 

1393 passed: 

1394 

1395 >>> Rational("1.23") 

1396 123/100 

1397 >>> Rational('1e-2') 

1398 1/100 

1399 >>> Rational(".1") 

1400 1/10 

1401 >>> Rational('1e-2/3.2') 

1402 1/320 

1403 

1404 The conversion of other types of strings can be handled by 

1405 the sympify() function, and conversion of floats to expressions 

1406 or simple fractions can be handled with nsimplify: 

1407 

1408 >>> S('.[3]') # repeating digits in brackets 

1409 1/3 

1410 >>> S('3**2/10') # general expressions 

1411 9/10 

1412 >>> nsimplify(.3) # numbers that have a simple form 

1413 3/10 

1414 

1415 But if the input does not reduce to a literal Rational, an error will 

1416 be raised: 

1417 

1418 >>> Rational(pi) 

1419 Traceback (most recent call last): 

1420 ... 

1421 TypeError: invalid input: pi 

1422 

1423 

1424 Low-level 

1425 --------- 

1426 

1427 Access numerator and denominator as .p and .q: 

1428 

1429 >>> r = Rational(3, 4) 

1430 >>> r 

1431 3/4 

1432 >>> r.p 

1433 3 

1434 >>> r.q 

1435 4 

1436 

1437 Note that p and q return integers (not SymPy Integers) so some care 

1438 is needed when using them in expressions: 

1439 

1440 >>> r.p/r.q 

1441 0.75 

1442 

1443 See Also 

1444 ======== 

1445 sympify, sympy.simplify.simplify.nsimplify 

1446 """ 

1447 is_real = True 

1448 is_integer = False 

1449 is_rational = True 

1450 is_number = True 

1451 

1452 __slots__ = ['p', 'q'] 

1453 

1454 is_Rational = True 

1455 

1456 @cacheit 

1457 def __new__(cls, p, q=None, gcd=None): 

1458 if q is None: 

1459 if isinstance(p, Rational): 

1460 return p 

1461 

1462 if isinstance(p, SYMPY_INTS): 

1463 pass 

1464 else: 

1465 if isinstance(p, (float, Float)): 

1466 return Rational(*_as_integer_ratio(p)) 

1467 

1468 if not isinstance(p, string_types): 

1469 try: 

1470 p = sympify(p) 

1471 except (SympifyError, SyntaxError): 

1472 pass # error will raise below 

1473 else: 

1474 if p.count('/') > 1: 

1475 raise TypeError('invalid input: %s' % p) 

1476 p = p.replace(' ', '') 

1477 pq = p.rsplit('/', 1) 

1478 if len(pq) == 2: 

1479 p, q = pq 

1480 fp = fractions.Fraction(p) 

1481 fq = fractions.Fraction(q) 

1482 p = fp/fq 

1483 try: 

1484 p = fractions.Fraction(p) 

1485 except ValueError: 

1486 pass # error will raise below 

1487 else: 

1488 return Rational(p.numerator, p.denominator, 1) 

1489 

1490 if not isinstance(p, Rational): 

1491 raise TypeError('invalid input: %s' % p) 

1492 

1493 q = 1 

1494 gcd = 1 

1495 else: 

1496 p = Rational(p) 

1497 q = Rational(q) 

1498 

1499 if isinstance(q, Rational): 

1500 p *= q.q 

1501 q = q.p 

1502 if isinstance(p, Rational): 

1503 q *= p.q 

1504 p = p.p 

1505 

1506 # p and q are now integers 

1507 if q == 0: 

1508 if p == 0: 

1509 if _errdict["divide"]: 

1510 raise ValueError("Indeterminate 0/0") 

1511 else: 

1512 return S.NaN 

1513 return S.ComplexInfinity 

1514 if q < 0: 

1515 q = -q 

1516 p = -p 

1517 if not gcd: 

1518 gcd = igcd(abs(p), q) 

1519 if gcd > 1: 

1520 p //= gcd 

1521 q //= gcd 

1522 if q == 1: 

1523 return Integer(p) 

1524 if p == 1 and q == 2: 

1525 return S.Half 

1526 obj = Expr.__new__(cls) 

1527 obj.p = p 

1528 obj.q = q 

1529 return obj

1539

1660 def _eval_power(self, expt): 

1661 if isinstance(expt, Number): 

1662 if isinstance(expt, Float): 

1663 return self._eval_evalf(expt._prec)**expt 

1664 if expt.is_negative: 

1665 # (3/4)**-2 -> (4/3)**2 

1666 ne = -expt 

1667 if (ne is S.One): 

1668 return Rational(self.q, self.p) 

1669 if self.is_negative: 

1670 return S.NegativeOne**expt*Rational(self.q, -self.p)**ne 

1671 else: 

1672 return Rational(self.q, self.p)**ne 

1673 if expt is S.Infinity: # -oo already caught by test for negative 

1674 if self.p > self.q: 

1675 # (3/2)**oo -> oo 

1676 return S.Infinity 

1677 if self.p < -self.q: 

1678 # (-3/2)**oo -> oo + I*oo 

1679 return S.Infinity + S.Infinity*S.ImaginaryUnit 

1680 return S.Zero 

1681 if isinstance(expt, Integer): 

1682 # (4/3)**2 -> 4**2 / 3**2 

1683 return Rational(self.p**expt.p, self.q**expt.p, 1) 

1684 if isinstance(expt, Rational): 

1685 if self.p != 1: 

1686 # (4/3)**(5/6) -> 4**(5/6)*3**(-5/6) 

1687 return Integer(self.p)**expt*Integer(self.q)**(-expt) 

1688 # as the above caught negative self.p, now self is positive 

1689 return Integer(self.q)**Rational( 

1690 expt.p*(expt.q - 1), expt.q) / \ 

1691 Integer(self.q)**Integer(expt.p) 

1692 

1693 if self.is_negative and expt.is_even: 

1694 return (-self)**expt

1883class Integer(Rational): 

1884 """Represents integer numbers of any size. 

1885 

1886 Examples 

1887 ======== 

1888 

1889 >>> from sympy import Integer 

1890 >>> Integer(3) 

1891 3 

1892 

1893 If a float or a rational is passed to Integer, the fractional part 

1894 will be discarded; the effect is of rounding toward zero. 

1895 

1896 >>> Integer(3.8) 

1897 3 

1898 >>> Integer(-3.8) 

1899 -3 

1900 

1901 A string is acceptable input if it can be parsed as an integer: 

1902 

1903 >>> Integer("9" * 20) 

1904 99999999999999999999 

1905 

1906 It is rarely needed to explicitly instantiate an Integer, because 

1907 Python integers are automatically converted to Integer when they 

1908 are used in SymPy expressions.

2133 def _eval_power(self, expt): 

2134 """ 

2135 Tries to do some simplifications on self**expt 

2136 

2137 Returns None if no further simplifications can be done 

2138 

2139 When exponent is a fraction (so we have for example a square root), 

2140 we try to find a simpler representation by factoring the argument 

2141 up to factors of 2**15, e.g. 

2142 

2143 - sqrt(4) becomes 2 

2144 - sqrt(-4) becomes 2*I 

2145 - (2**(3+7)*3**(6+7))**Rational(1,7) becomes 6*18**(3/7) 

2146 

2147 Further simplification would require a special call to factorint on 

2148 the argument which is not done here for sake of speed. 

2149 

2150 """ 

2151 from sympy import perfect_power 

2152 

2153 if expt is S.Infinity: 

2154 if self.p > S.One: 

2155 return S.Infinity 

2156 # cases -1, 0, 1 are done in their respective classes 

2157 return S.Infinity + S.ImaginaryUnit*S.Infinity 

2158 if expt is S.NegativeInfinity: 

2159 return Rational(1, self)**S.Infinity 

2160 if not isinstance(expt, Number): 

2161 # simplify when expt is even 

2162 # (-2)**k --> 2**k 

2163 if self.is_negative and expt.is_even: 

2164 return (-self)**expt 

2165 if isinstance(expt, Float): 

2166 # Rational knows how to exponentiate by a Float 

2167 return super(Integer, self)._eval_power(expt) 

2168 if not isinstance(expt, Rational): 

2169 return 

2170 if expt is S.Half and self.is_negative: 

2171 # we extract I for this special case since everyone is doing so 

2172 return S.ImaginaryUnit*Pow(-self, expt) 

2173 if expt.is_negative: 

2174 # invert base and change sign on exponent 

2175 ne = -expt 

2176 if self.is_negative: 

2177 return S.NegativeOne**expt*Rational(1, -self)**ne 

2178 else: 

2179 return Rational(1, self.p)**ne 

2180 # see if base is a perfect root, sqrt(4) --> 2 

2181 x, xexact = integer_nthroot(abs(self.p), expt.q) 

2182 if xexact: 

2183 # if it's a perfect root we've finished 

2184 result = Integer(x**abs(expt.p)) 

2185 if self.is_negative: 

2186 result *= S.NegativeOne**expt 

2187 return result 

2188 

2189 # The following is an algorithm where we collect perfect roots 

2190 # from the factors of base. 

2191 

2192 # if it's not an nth root, it still might be a perfect power 

2193 b_pos = int(abs(self.p)) 

2194 p = perfect_power(b_pos) 

2195 if p is not False: 

2196 dict = {p[0]: p[1]} 

2197 else: 

2198 dict = Integer(b_pos).factors(limit=2**15) 

2199 

2200 # now process the dict of factors 

2201 out_int = 1 # integer part 

2202 out_rad = 1 # extracted radicals 

2203 sqr_int = 1 

2204 sqr_gcd = 0 

2205 sqr_dict = {} 

2206 for prime, exponent in dict.items(): 

2207 exponent *= expt.p 

2208 # remove multiples of expt.q: (2**12)**(1/10) -> 2*(2**2)**(1/10) 

2209 div_e, div_m = divmod(exponent, expt.q) 

2210 if div_e > 0: 

2211 out_int *= prime**div_e 

2212 if div_m > 0: 

2213 # see if the reduced exponent shares a gcd with e.q 

2214 # (2**2)**(1/10) -> 2**(1/5) 

2215 g = igcd(div_m, expt.q) 

2216 if g != 1: 

2217 out_rad *= Pow(prime, Rational(div_m//g, expt.q//g)) 

2218 else: 

2219 sqr_dict[prime] = div_m 

2220 # identify gcd of remaining powers 

2221 for p, ex in sqr_dict.items(): 

2222 if sqr_gcd == 0: 

2223 sqr_gcd = ex 

2224 else: 

2225 sqr_gcd = igcd(sqr_gcd, ex) 

2226 if sqr_gcd == 1: 

2227 break 

2228 for k, v in sqr_dict.items(): 

2229 sqr_int *= k**(v//sqr_gcd) 

2230 if sqr_int == b_pos and out_int == 1 and out_rad == 1: 

2231 result = None 

2232 else: 

2233 result = out_int*out_rad*Pow(sqr_int, Rational(sqr_gcd, expt.q)) 

2234 if self.is_negative: 

2235 result *= Pow(S.NegativeOne, expt) 

2236 return result

2263class AlgebraicNumber(Expr): 

2264 """Class for representing algebraic numbers in SymPy. """ 

2265 

2266 __slots__ = ['rep', 'root', 'alias', 'minpoly'] 

2267 

2268 is_AlgebraicNumber = True 

2269 is_algebraic = True 

2270 is_number = True

2272 def __new__(cls, expr, coeffs=None, alias=None, **args): 

2273 """Construct a new algebraic number. """ 

2274 from sympy import Poly 

2275 from sympy.polys.polyclasses import ANP, DMP 

2276 from sympy.polys.numberfields import minimal_polynomial 

2277 from sympy.core.symbol import Symbol 

2278 

2279 expr = sympify(expr) 

2280 

2281 if isinstance(expr, (tuple, Tuple)): 

2282 minpoly, root = expr 

2283 

2284 if not minpoly.is_Poly: 

2285 minpoly = Poly(minpoly) 

2286 elif expr.is_AlgebraicNumber: 

2287 minpoly, root = expr.minpoly, expr.root 

2288 else: 

2289 minpoly, root = minimal_polynomial( 

2290 expr, args.get('gen'), polys=True), expr 

2291 

2292 dom = minpoly.get_domain() 

2293 

2294 if coeffs is not None: 

2295 if not isinstance(coeffs, ANP): 

2296 rep = DMP.from_sympy_list(sympify(coeffs), 0, dom) 

2297 scoeffs = Tuple(*coeffs) 

2298 else: 

2299 rep = DMP.from_list(coeffs.to_list(), 0, dom) 

2300 scoeffs = Tuple(*coeffs.to_list()) 

2301 

2302 if rep.degree() >= minpoly.degree(): 

2303 rep = rep.rem(minpoly.rep) 

2304 

2305 else: 

2306 rep = DMP.from_list([1, 0], 0, dom) 

2307 scoeffs = Tuple(1, 0) 

2308 

2309 sargs = (root, scoeffs) 

2310 

2311 if alias is not None: 

2312 if not isinstance(alias, Symbol): 

2313 alias = Symbol(alias) 

2314 sargs = sargs + (alias,) 

2315 

2316 obj = Expr.__new__(cls, *sargs) 

2317 

2318 obj.rep = rep 

2319 obj.root = root 

2320 obj.alias = alias 

2321 obj.minpoly = minpoly 

2322 

2323 return obj

2359 def to_algebraic_integer(self): 

2360 """Convert ``self`` to an algebraic integer. """ 

2361 from sympy import Poly 

2362 f = self.minpoly 

2363 

2364 if f.LC() == 1: 

2365 return self 

2366 

2367 coeff = f.LC()**(f.degree() - 1) 

2368 poly = f.compose(Poly(f.gen/f.LC())) 

2369 

2370 minpoly = poly*coeff 

2371 root = f.LC()*self.root 

2372 

2373 return AlgebraicNumber((minpoly, root), self.coeffs())

2375 def _eval_simplify(self, ratio, measure, rational, inverse): 

2376 from sympy.polys import CRootOf, minpoly 

2377 

2378 for r in [r for r in self.minpoly.all_roots() if r.func != CRootOf]: 

2379 if minpoly(self.root - r).is_Symbol: 

2380 # use the matching root if it's simpler 

2381 if measure(r) < ratio*measure(self.root): 

2382 return AlgebraicNumber(r) 

2383 return self

3079class NaN(with_metaclass(Singleton, Number)): 

3080 """ 

3081 Not a Number. 

3082 

3083 This serves as a place holder for numeric values that are indeterminate. 

3084 Most operations on NaN, produce another NaN. Most indeterminate forms, 

3085 such as ``0/0`` or ``oo - oo` produce NaN. Two exceptions are ``0**0`` 

3086 and ``oo**0``, which all produce ``1`` (this is consistent with Python's 

3087 float). 

3088 

3089 NaN is loosely related to floating point nan, which is defined in the 

3090 IEEE 754 floating point standard, and corresponds to the Python 

3091 ``float('nan')``. Differences are noted below. 

3092 

3093 NaN is mathematically not equal to anything else, even NaN itself. This 

3094 explains the initially counter-intuitive results with ``Eq`` and ``==`` in 

3095 the examples below. 

3096 

3097 NaN is not comparable so inequalities raise a TypeError. This is in 

3098 constrast with floating point nan where all inequalities are false. 

3099 

3100 NaN is a singleton, and can be accessed by ``S.NaN``, or can be imported 

3101 as ``nan``. 

3102 

3103 Examples 

3104 ======== 

3105 

3106 >>> from sympy import nan, S, oo, Eq 

3107 >>> nan is S.NaN 

3108 True 

3109 >>> oo - oo 

3110 nan 

3111 >>> nan + 1 

3112 nan 

3113 >>> Eq(nan, nan) # mathematical equality 

3114 False 

3115 >>> nan == nan # structural equality 

3116 True 

3117

3543class TribonacciConstant(with_metaclass(Singleton, NumberSymbol)):

3549 preceding three terms.
